## Open Questions / Why Simultaneous Merging Fails

> [!WARNING]
> **Why we cannot average neural network weights**
> In deep learning, you cannot simply average the weights of two independently trained models (e.g., `model_C = (model_A + model_B) / 2`). Because the mathematical space is so complex (non-convex), Model A and Model B will learn completely different pathways to solve the same problem. If you average them, the pathways collide and break, resulting in a model that outputs pure garbage/static noise. This is especially true for GANs and Transformers.

**The Solution: Sequential Chunking**
The mathematically sound way to do this is **Sequential Checkpointing**:
1. Run Notebook A for 12 hours (Epochs 1-50). It saves `epoch_50.pth`.
2. Start Notebook B, upload `epoch_50.pth`, and tell it to resume from there for another 12 hours (Epochs 51-100).
3. Start Notebook C, upload `epoch_100.pth`, and resume (Epochs 101-150).

This guarantees the model continuously builds on its own knowledge without breaking.

